eristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud FitzIngram was born in 1188, her father, Mr. Ingram, was 27 and her mother, Mrs. Ingram, was 24. She married Gerard de Stirap in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Cir 1188–":"1188–Surnud","1188–Female":"1188–Surnud","1186–Male":"1186–Surnud","1212–Female":"1212–Surnud","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1212":"1212","1188":"1188","1165":"1165","1186":"1186","Cir 1188":"1188","about 1212":"umbes 1212","1162":"1162","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stirap, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"Cir 1188–":"1188–Kuollut","1188–Female":"1188–Kuollut","1186–Male":"1186–Kuollut","1212–Female":"1212–Kuollut","1162–Male":"1162–Kuollut","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1212":"1212","1188":"1188","1165":"1165","1186":"1186","Cir 1188":"1188","about 1212":"noin 1212","1162":"1162","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunt